Logging and Error Handling (Robustness)\par
\par
We will implement extensive logging and error handling throughout the application, across all components, to ensure reliability and ease of maintenance. This is a critical aspect of a professional-grade app \endash  it aids in debugging, monitoring, and providing a seamless user experience\par
zeepalm.com\par
. Key points in our logging and error strategy:\par
\par
Comprehensive Logging: Every important action and event in the system will be logged. On the backend, this means logging all critical operations (user logins, API requests, database queries for key data changes, payment transactions, etc.) at appropriate log levels (info, warning, error)\par
zeepalm.com\par
. For example, when a trainer creates a new workout plan, an info log will record that event (with trainer and client ID), and if a failure occurs (like a database error), an error log will capture the stack trace and context. On the mobile app, we\rquote ll also log client-side events: app screens visited, buttons clicked, and any errors/exceptions in the app logic or network calls. These client logs can be sent to the backend or an analytics service for aggregate analysis.\par
\par
Structured and Secure Logs: We will use a structured logging format (such as JSON) for server logs to make them easy to search and analyze\par
zeepalm.com\par
zeepalm.com\par
. Logs will include contextual information like timestamps, user IDs or session IDs, and function names to trace what happened. We must also scrub sensitive information from logs \endash  no personal data (like passwords, or even private user content) should appear in logs to protect privacy\par
zeepalm.com\par
. Regular reviews of log content will ensure we aren\rquote t accidentally logging PII (Personally Identifiable Information) or health data. We will implement log rotation and retention policies to manage log file sizes and archive older logs securely\par
zeepalm.com\par
.\par
\par
Error Handling Strategy: The app will be built with a defensive programming mindset. We will use try-catch blocks in critical areas of code and handle exceptions gracefully. On the backend, any unexpected error will return a controlled error response to the client (avoiding exposing internal stack traces to users). Errors will be logged with high severity and, where appropriate, alerts sent to developers (for example, integrating our logs with an alerting system or using an error tracking tool like Sentry that can email the dev team on each crash). On the front end, if something fails (like a network request), the app should catch it and show a user-friendly message (e.g. \ldblquote Unable to load data, please check your connection\rdblquote  instead of just crashing or hanging). We\rquote ll also implement global error handlers \endash  for instance, a centralized place in the app to catch any uncaught exceptions so they can be logged and the app can recover or prompt the user to restart if needed\par
diegomarcher.medium.com\par
.\par
\par
Crash Reporting: We will integrate crash reporting specifically for the mobile apps (using Crashlytics or Sentry). This will automatically capture the device state and stack trace when the app crashes or hits an exception, and send it to our dashboard. With this, we can quickly identify issues happening in production that may not have been caught in testing. It\rquote s crucial for maintaining app stability that we monitor crashes and errors in real-time and issue bug-fix updates promptly\par
uxcam.com\par
.\par
\par
Performance Monitoring: Alongside logging and error handling, we\rquote ll monitor performance metrics (like API response times, app launch time, memory usage) through logs or analytics. This helps catch issues like slow database queries or memory leaks early. For example, we might log a warning if an API call takes more than a certain threshold, indicating a potential performance bottleneck.\par
\par
Extensive Testing and QA: While not exactly logging, having a strong testing phase (unit tests, integration tests, and user testing) is part of error handling strategy. We aim to catch as many bugs as possible before release. Automated tests will cover core functionality (e.g. calculation of calories, workout scheduling logic, permission roles) so that regressions are caught early. Quality Assurance will also test edge cases (like network loss, weird user input) to ensure the app handles them without crashing. Wherever a bug is found, we will add logging around it if applicable, to ensure if it ever happens again in production, we get details.\par
\par
By prioritizing logging and thorough error handling, we ensure that as the application grows, we can maintain stability and quickly diagnose any issues that arise\par
zeepalm.com\par
. This level of \ldblquote extreme\rdblquote  logging will prove invaluable for troubleshooting and improving the app continuously. Users benefit by experiencing a more reliable app, and developers benefit by having the data needed to fix problems and optimize the system.\par
